message.raw:
Fix an issue with making calls to add_text asynchronous. Whilst that change was
necessary to ensure printing large amounts of text from the mainloop doesn't
deadlock, it means that shutdown() no longer guarantees that future queued
inmain calls to add_text will not run, and any such calls may crash since qt
widgets may have been destroyed.

This commit fixes the issue by having shutdown() call add_text sychronously
until there is no more queued text remaining. Future calls to add_text see that
there is nothing left to do and return without touching Qt objects.

message.raw:
Make outputbox more responsive for large numbers of lines.

The time to print lines to the GUI scales with the number of lines, and for only
modest numbers of lines, the processing time in the GUI thread exceeds the overhead
of posting the function call to the main thread. Therefore one might as well
make smaller batches, and update the GUI more frequently to not hang the GUI in
one large call and so that output is continuously produced rather than all at
once after a hang. A batch size as small as ten seems to have good performance.

using inmain_decorator(False) also seems to make output faster.

This change actually seems to make output faster all up, i.e. more throughput,
not just better responsiveness. I'm not quite sure why, but it is a nice improvement.

message.raw:
Added charformat keyword argument to OutputBox.write(). This makes it compatible
with being the stream assigned to a zprocess.RichStreamHandler logging handler,
allowing colourised logging to an outputbox.

Added file-like stub methods to OutputBox so that it can be used in place of a
file-like object.

Add aliases for formatting based on log levels.

Fix failure to memoise text formatting.

Add font name as a varaible instead of using a string literal where it's used

Remove use of 'red' string favouring the RED variable instead.

Fixed bug which caused obscure error message due to font loading being attempted
after an exception in the main thread (`__file__` doesn't exist as seen from the
thread apparantly - now we save the fonts location in a global varaible earlier)

message.raw:
PySide2 support

PySide2 looks to be the future of Qt in Python so I figured we should add support,
it was not too hard.

The version of PySide2 in conda-forge at the moment is an alpha and has some
missing widgets and raises NotImplementedErrors on a few things, so labscript programs
are not working perfectly. But these are issues with PySide2, not qtutils.

The only issue I've seen that might be the a problem with qtutils so far is that the outputbox
text isn't white. Not sure why.

There are other rough edges - some PySide2 methods appear to not accept say, integers,
requiring the right Qt datatype such as a Qt.Checkstate. So where integers have
been saved to config files, when restored they need to be wrapped in Qt.CheckState(int) before being
used in Qt methods. And they will need to converted to integers before being saved to the config file
so that they are compatible betwen Qt wrappers. This means labscript programs are all erroring on
loading their config files.

Either PySide2 will sort issues like this out (it seems to be in very active development at the moment)
or fixes can be applied to the applications. There is plenty of time, but basic
qtutils support seems to be step 1 so here it is.

For now PySide2 is listed as the lowest priority Qt lib in qtutils.qt, so it
is unlikely anyone will have issues for the moment, but I expect it will be more
widely used in the future and probably become the default Qt in
Anaconda.

The only issue I've seen that might be the a problem with qtutils so far is that the outputbox
text isn't white. Not sure why.

There are other rough edges - some PySide2 methods appear to not accept say, integers,
requiring the right Qt datatype such as a Qt.Checkstate. So where integers have
been saved to config files, when restored they need to be wrapped in Qt.CheckState(int) before being
used in Qt methods. And they will need to converted to integers before being saved to the config file
so that they are compatible betwen Qt wrappers. This means labscript programs are all erroring on
loading their config files.

Either PySide2 will sort issues like this out (it seems to be in very active development at the moment)
or fixes can be applied to the applications. There is plenty of time, but basic
qtutils support seems to be step 1 so here it is.

For now PySide2 is listed as the lowest priority Qt lib in qtutils.qt, so it
is unlikely anyone will have issues for the moment, but I expect it will be more
widely used in the future and probably become the default Qt in
Anaconda.
